  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Gedo Education Capacity Building</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Somalia, secondary schooling is crucial to create professionals who will rebuild the country. Somalia&#x2019;s secondary school system is very poor, and many girls, disabled children and boys (to join militias) drop out. In Gedo region, the project&#x2019;s target area bordering Kenya and Ethiopia, the education sector was deserted and became dilapidated during the conflict. The region has only three public secondary schools, built mainly by Diaspora communities. Secondary teachers are often untrained or poorly trained, with no in-service training or skills upgrading available. Many local teachers only enter the profession as a survival strategy. This project will widen access for pupils, especially girls and disabled children, to quality secondary education. It will focus on developing an improved curriculum, training teachers, supporting Community Education Committees, (CECs) to manage schools, working with 70 community leaders to raise awareness of the importance of education, and applying learning gained to advocate for replication in other parts of Somalia. Overseen by HIRDA UK, it will be implemented by respected local organisation, Action for Relief and Development, (ARD), and should result in a new curriculum, 35 teachers trained to deliver it, a 30% increase in girls and disabled students enrolling.</narrative>
  </description>
